			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Actually, here in Wyoming (kinda the epicenter for most of North America's dinosaur digs) there is a huge abundance of fossil fuels. Cambell County in NE Wyoming boasts over 1/4 of the total national coal reserves. The company I work for supports the Oil & Gas industry including a big project underway revitalizing an older oil field for more production. Political historians know the region as the crux of the Teapot Dome scandal. While the reserves were considered too costly to retrieve oil from in the 90s, recent technology makes it possible to retrieve oil at a greater rate than ever before for another 40 years or so. I'm not an expert in oil and gas exploration, but either this is a case of the oil always being there and technology improvements making it attainable or its another case supporting the claim of inorganic creation of oil.
<br />

<br />
Just thought it interesting that both therioes are somewhat supported by this region.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
