			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				A Uranium core that was stable at that temperature with that much pressure? I doubt this. The tidal movements of the mantle etc. would create massive compression on a core of any makeup, a core of volatile Uranium would have serious issues staying stable under that pressure/heat combination. 
<br />

<br />
   Secondly: If this was true, would not the ions from this massive Uranium Ball find their way surface-ward? I know Iron Ions do.
<br />

<br />
  Thirdly: self sustaining/regenerating reactions are (as far as modern scientists know) a myth. The laws of Thermodynamics clearly state that: As entropy decreases in a system, entropy OUTSIDE the system increases, while at the same time: entropy is ALWAYS increasing. This means that if this self sustaining/regenerating reaction (read: increase/then equal decrease in entropy) we would be seeing massive entropy increase OUTSIDE this system, the heat output of the core would not be the only product, Charged particles, nasty radioactive ions, etc. would also occur.
<br />

<br />
  The reason for continued heat is twofold: The sun: The specific heat of the mantle/magma/the core. When that heat is high (which it most certainly is) it retains heat better. Basic Chemistry. I don't know what Irons specific heat is, or what the specific heat of the mantle is, but I am sure it is high, and this would provide. There is no need for a reaction if the specific heat of the core/inner mantle/outer mantle is high enough. Also, the tidal/circulatory movements of the mantle allow heat to be transferred in a convective manner, like your oven. It is efficient and powerful.
<br />

<br />
And I agree, if the inorganic oil theory proves true, and an easy way to replicate the instance required to make it is found, then the world can enjoy oil-driven economic success for a longer time.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
