				<div class="postbody">
				I know oil doesn't come from dinosaurs like they just pissed the stuff out or something, but just for example a slang-term for some motor oil is 'dino oil' (as opposed to synthetic).  I know one or two things about hydrocarbons, but it is just easier to say petroleum came from dinos.
<br />

<br />
Anyhow, as far as I understand it the Earth's core is indeed primarily composed of molten iron along with smaller amounts of various heavy elements.  The Earth's core being composed primarily of Uranium is a relatively new theory, but I do not think it is widely accepted at all.  The density of iron and uranium is massive and if the core was indeed primarily composed of uranium we would have known a long while ago.
<br />

<br />
Iron is radioactive to the degree that it will go thru beta (I think) emission; obviously, though, not like the more widely known 'radioactive' elements.
<br />
Helium is also arguably the most abundant element in the universe, so not too hard to understand why it would have a significant prescence in and on the Earth.<br />
