				<div class="postbody">
				The fission core information is here: <a href="http://nuclearplanet.com/" target="_blank">http://nuclearplanet.com/</a>
<br />

<br />
The conventional wisdom is that it is iron. The conventional wisdom also completely fails to provide workable experimental models for both the magnetic field and the occasional shifts in the magnetic poles. The models don't quite fit the recorded data. Therefore, the conventional wisdom is probably close, but definitely wrong. At least a little.
<br />

<br />
This guy has come up with the fission core theory to try and address the discrepancies. His theory does provide workable models that are more accurate with respect to recorded data than those provided by the conventional iron-core theory. His theory has so far survived all professional review, and remains plausible. It's hardly far fetched, and there is no data to prove it wrong. Yet.
<br />

<br />
As for who is right... well that'll have to wait until we have a way to look through thousands of miles of rock.<br />
