				<div class="postbody">
				I say that the big chunk of the core can not be Uranium is due to seismic testing that has been done for years and years by scientists all over the world.  The density of uranium and iron is like night or day.  No way that hundreds of scientists could make an easy error about mistaking the two.
<br />
If it was indeed mostly uranium it would have been noted a long time ago that the core is more dense than what would be theorized.
<br />

<br />
Iron and uranium don't get along too well.  However nickel and iron do (obviously) and that guy's article mentions nickel.
<br />

<br />
I readily accept that the core can and will contain many other heavy metals, but the primary composition will be of iron and/or nickel.
<br />
I will also readily accept that there may be vast amounts of uranium in the mantle or other portions of the Earth's inner crust that could indeed by conducive to the geoactivity of the planet.
<br />

<br />
It would take a lot of solid proof to convince me we got a giant chunk of uranium sitting in the middle of our planet.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
