			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Many years ago I saw a thing (On Nova probably, but I don't recall specifically) about the creation of Oil.
<br />

<br />
They basically proved it is organic by doing core sample mining in the Peat Bogs of the UK. Centuries (or millenia) of peat moss growing on top of itself, adding weight and pressure to the lower levels as it compressed down.
<br />

<br />
Once they drilled down about 200 feet, they found that the moss had been squished into a hydrocarbon soup that was very similar to crude oil.
<br />

<br />
Some of the oil will have come from dinosaurs, but animal life just doesn't grow in the kind of consistancy and concentration as basic plant life. Most of the oil used to be plankton, or peat moss, or any one of a dozen kinds of dense, durable vegetation that occupied the same spot for a very long time. Like anything in Geology, it's an issue of raw materials, pressure, and time.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
