				<div class="postbody">
				Poppa, going to try to be nice but you just entirely oversimplified the entire sciences of physics and chemistry.  And, not in a good way.
<br />

<br />
The weight of a molecule is just a small portion of what the characteristics are.  Lighter things don't always go up, and heavier things don't always go down.  For instance water (H2O) has a molecular weight of 18amu, yet the bulk of our atmosphere is made up of nitrogen (diatomic element, N2) has a weight of 28amu.  But, wait, nitrogen goes 'up' and water goes 'down.'
<br />

<br />
Uranium may be heavier than iron, but the chemical properties or uranium makes it very unlikey to 'mix' with iron; almost like an oil and water thing going on.
<br />

<br />
Poppa, you must know only one geologist who is clueless.  Seismic testing has been pretty conclusive for many, many things.  Just not everything.  I think that it is known pretty well what the consistency is, just not the exact composition.
<br />

<br />
So, I had a wee bit of time and did some net surfing on this topic.  Found a few interesting pages:
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://geology.about.com/library/weekly/aa072102a.htm" target="_blank" class="postlink">LINK</a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.sciencentral.com/articles/view.php3?language=english&type=24119&article_id=218391927&cat=2_5" target="_blank" class="postlink">LINK</a>
<br />
<a href="http://geology.about.com/library/weekly/aa081599a.htm" target="_blank" class="postlink">LINK</a>
<br />

<br />
I am all for the advancment of science, however those theories must be parsimonious; they must make sense.<br />
