			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				There are only two requirements to a hypothesis or theorem.
<br />

<br />
1) It must match available data.
<br />

<br />
2) It must make predections that can be tested and verified to determine its accuracy.
<br />

<br />
Making sense does not necessarily matter, particularly when a new theory overturns all known and accepted models, as has happened countless times in the past. It just has to match the data, that's all. Everything we know right now is a "best guess" and I'd be willing to bet if you were to get a look at where science is in a hundred years you'd think you were living in the stone age on a flat earth by comparison. It's best not to greet new ideas with a "that's @#%$" response unless there's data at hand to properly refute it. Close-mindedness is the greatest enemy of science and progress.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
