			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				First off there are differences between a theory and a hypothesis and even moreso in the scientific field.  A common definition of a hypothesis is 'an educated guess' then you confuse the matter by having what is called a null hypothesis, but we will ignore that.  
<br />
A scienctific theory is essentially a 'law' in that it is some sort of phenomena that has a staggering amount of evidence.  Theories are by and large dynamic and more broad in scope than a 'law.'  For example many, many people assume that gravity is just a theory; the theory of gravity.  This is because you can not actually see gravity, you can not put it into a beaker and perform an experiment on it.  You can not directly do any test on gravity, nor is there one simple mathematical proof for gravity.  However you infer the consquences of gravity by measuring other variables (e.g. light, mass, time, etc).  In fact the solar system is theorized to be heliocentric; that we revolve around the sun.  This is just a theory.  Nobody has actually stayed in one particular point in space for a course of multiple years to actually observe us circumnavigate the sun.
<br />
We, just like with gravity, take it for granted though.
<br />

<br />
I mention all of this hot air to try to show the significance of a scientific theory as opposed to a mere hypothesis and also to the fact that it is much more complicated than following two simple requirements.
<br />

<br />
Also many scientists love to throw out the word <span style="font-style: italic">parsimonious</span>.  Parsimonious in a scientific discussion basically means that if you have mulitple ideas to explain a phenomenon the one idea that meets the explanation and is the most simple of the ideas is therefore more readily accepted and likely to be true; Occam's Razor.
<br />

<br />
I think why so many scientific ideas from the past have been overturned is because of the general repressivness of government, church and society in the past.  We really do not experience this in the modern age, obviously to a degree when it comes to cloning humans but that is such an extreme; an outlier that can be ignored.
<br />
If the people in the future do not see us as 'living in the stone age' then more than likely we wiped our civilization.  For the sake of our species, I hope our future generations see us as somewhat primitive.
<br />

<br />
Anyhow, in this case about a huge %@$# uranium core there is evidence to support otherwise.  It is not just a matter of calling @#%$, but of actually reading and understanding one or two things about science.
<br />

<br />
More importantly, Raviel, the individual that wishes to change what is fundamentally accepted must be the one to show significant evidence.  It is not the responsibility of every other scientist to have data on hand to refute what is already accepted.
<br />

<br />
Who knows, maybe a geologist who can not get a job at a proper research institute may be right all along.  He, though, needs to show more evidence.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
